Car. 29.— mutavit: ,used absolutely as in Fam. 16. 1. 1.——-accubuit: Caesar followed the regular order, viz„ exercise, the bath, ᾱίηηεΥ.-ἑμετικὴν agebat (sc. τέχνην), lte was taking a course ofemetics. Emetics were regularly prescribed by physicians in order that patients might escape the effects resulting from eating elaborate dinners. They were taken in the morning, after the bath or after the cena. The use of them was, however, by no means confined to men of a gluttonous disposition ; cf. pro Deiot. 21, where the speaker certainly has every reason to avoid offending Caesar: cum . . . vomere post cenam te velle dixisses.
